[
    {
        "content": "<p>This seems to be saying that there is a use for non-integrable Dirac structures; i.e. they give an example where the Dirac structure is non-integrable and it seems like a physically important structure:<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/qqIjOA4LHleXb_XiGaPMYYOW/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/qqIjOA4LHleXb_XiGaPMYYOW/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/qqIjOA4LHleXb_XiGaPMYYOW/image.png\"></a></div>",
        "id": 272038372,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1644959330
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's interesting.  \"Non-holonomic constraint\" means precisely that some integrability conditions fail: you can move along a long path obeying the constraints to get from a state <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span> to some arbitrarily nearby state <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant=\"normal\" lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">′</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x&#x27;</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7519em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7519em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">′</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> that you <em>can't</em> get to using a <em>short</em> path that obeys the constraints.    So, this makes sense.</p>",
        "id": 272039412,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1644959793
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What does that correspond to in the euro example?</p>",
        "id": 272039545,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1644959866
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, I guess you can't shimmy the coin perpendicularly to its movement</p>",
        "id": 272039694,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1644959947
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Right.  I usually use the example of a ball \"rolling without slipping\" on a table.  You can get from any state to any other state, but if you have two nearby states they may not be connected by a short path with no slipping.</p>",
        "id": 272040808,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1644960494
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I wrote a paper once with John Huerta on how the exceptional Lie group <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>G</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G_2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> and the 'split octonions' arise from the problem of a ball rolling without slipping or twisting on a ball 3 times as big across.   There's something magic that happens at precisely this ratio of radii.</p>\n<p>There's an animation of it in these web pages:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/ball/\">Split octonions and the rolling ball</a></li>\n</ul>",
